 for bestpractices and # Terms of Service

## Overview
Create a Static Terms of Service page for Roam Resort that clearly communicates platform rules, usage terms for guests and hosts, disclaimers, and last-updated information. This page should integrate visually with the Roam Resort design system, support accessibility and SEO best practices, and connect with privacy/legal compliance tools that handle GDPR/CCPA requests (data export and account deletion) without exposing sensitive data on the TOS page itself. The implementation should be frontend-first, with backend hooks ready for future privacy flows, and strictly adhere to runtime safety rules for all code (null/undefined guards, proper array handling, and safe state initialization).

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A static, content-driven Terms of Service page that presents clear sections for guests and hosts, outlining permitted use, prohibited activities, payment terms, liability limitations, host responsibilities, and a brief disclaimer of warranties. It also includes a clearly displayed “Last Updated” date and a contact option for legal inquiries.

Goals:
- Present unambiguous contractual terms that protect Roam Resort and inform users.
- Provide a clean, editorial, luxury experience consistent with Roam Resort’s design system.
- Support accessibility, SEO (structured content, semantic headings), and responsive behavior.
- Tie into Privacy & Legal Compliance Tools in the project context, enabling future privacy request workflows (export, deletion) via a cohesive user journey from the Terms page to privacy tooling or via global footer links.

Connected features:
- Privacy & Legal Compliance Tools: Future-ready support for GDPR/CCPA requests (export data, delete account) with flows that can be invoked from the Terms page (e.g., via links in the footer or a dedicated Privacy section).
- No external APIs required for this page; content is static but fed by CMS-ready blocks for easy updates.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Header: Brand navigation with a subtle, transparent-to-solid navbar on scroll, consistent with the design system.
- Hero/Intro: A succinct hero area with a statement about terms and user obligations (optional, depending on design choices for the page).
- Content Sections: Distinct blocks for:
  - Acceptance and Scope
  - Services and Use Rules (Guests)
  - Services and Use Rules (Hosts)
  - Payment Terms
  - Liability and Disclaimers
  - Host Responsibilities
  - Termination and Suspension
  - Privacy & Data Rights (link to privacy tools, if applicable)
  - Last Updated Date
  - Contact Information
- Typography: Headlines in a serif display font; body text in a refined sans-serif; consistent with Roam Resort’s typography guidelines.
- Visual guidance: Editorial, spacious sections with generous padding (40–80px vertical spacing), soft shadows for content blocks, and subtle transitions on hover for interactive elements.
- Accessibility: All text should be legible (color contrast, font size options, screen-reader friendly headings and landmarks). Include skip-to-content accessibility and proper aria-labels for interactive elements.
- SEO: Use semantic HTML (main, nav, section, article, h1–h6), descriptive heading structure, meta description hint, and structured data where appropriate.

API integrations:
- No live API calls required for page rendering. Content should be easily fed by CMS or static content files and be ready for dynamic CMS wiring if desired.

## Components to Build
- TermsLayout (Container)
  - Props: sections (array), lastUpdated (date), contactInfo (object)
  - Responsibilities: Render page chrome, header, content sections, and footer area with last updated date and contact link.
- SectionCard (Reusable content block)
  - Props: id, title, body, bullets or list items, disclaimer text, list type
  - Style: Card with soft shadow, rounded corners, subtle borders
- HeroBar (Optional, depending on design)
  - Props: title, subtitle, backgroundImage (optional)
- SectionHeader (Typography + Section Label)
  - Props: label, title, subtitle
- AccessibilityToolbar (Optional per project standards)
  - Features: Skip-to-content link, font size toggles, high-contrast mode toggle (if part of design system)
- PrivacyLinkBlock (CTA / Link area)
  - Props: label, href, tier (e.g., primary or ghost)
- FooterLinks (Footer with privacy/legal links)
  - Props: links array (each with text and href), lastUpdated

All code must guard against null/undefined values before calling array methods. Follow runtime safety rules:
- Use data ?? [] for arrays derived from API or CMS (even if not used on this page, ensure safe defaults).
- When mapping or filtering, use (sections ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(sections) ? sections.map(...) : [].
- Initialize state with useState([]) for any array-type state.
- Validate API shapes (if any data is pulled) using Array.isArray(data?.sections) ? data.sections : [].
- Use optional chaining for nested objects (section?.title, section?.content).
- Destructure with defaults where applicable (const { sections = [], lastUpdated = "" } = props ?? {}).

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Create a TermsOfServicePage component that renders:
  - A top navigation bar (transparent over hero, solid on scroll) with accessible menu items.
  - A main article area with semantic sections and H2/H3 headings.
  - A Last Updated date displayed in a human-friendly format.
  - A Contact Us block or link for legal inquiries.
  - Links to Privacy & Data Rights (privacy tools) if applicable in global footer or within a dedicated section.
- UI components to implement (reuse or extend existing design system components):
  - Card, Button, Typography, Grid/Container, Image/Media block, Section
  - Ensure buttons use bronze-gold (#A97C50) with proper text contrast; secondary actions use soft beige with bronze outline as per design system.
  - Implement hover states, focus states, and accessible keyboard navigation.
- Accessibility:
  - ARIA labels for interactive elements, landmark regions, skip-to-content, and proper heading order.
  - Color contrast checks against WCAG AA standards.
- Responsiveness:
  - Fluid grid with breakpoints to stack sections on small screens.
  - Maintain generous spacing across breakpoints (40–80px sections, 24–32px padding inside blocks).
- SEO:
  - Use a clear H1 for the page, meaningful meta description, canonical URL if used in a SPA, and structured content for search indexing.

### Backend
- No API endpoints required for the TOS page itself; prepare data models and endpoints for future integration if privacy tools are wired here:
  - PrivacyRequest (future): id, userId, type (export/delete), status, requestedAt, completedAt
  - TermsPageContent (optional CMS hook): id, locale, lastUpdated, sections array
- Database migration stubs and type definitions ready for future adoption, with safe defaults to avoid runtime errors if data is missing.

### Integration
- Content injection pattern:
  - TermsOfServicePage should accept a sections prop that can be populated by CMS or static data. Guard all mappings with Array.isArray(sections) or (sections ?? []).
  - If a CMS provides a structured content object, normalize to a sections array: const normalizedSections = Array.isArray(content?.sections) ? content.sections : [].
- Privacy Tools integration point:
  - Include a Privacy & Data Rights CTA in the page (or via global footer) that routes to PrivacyTools or opens a modal if applicable. Ensure the link uses a safe href and accessible label.
- State management:
  - If you introduce local UI state (e.g., expand/collapse for long terms subsections), initialize with useState<any[]>([]) or appropriate type: useState<string[]>([]) for expanded section IDs.
- Theming:
  - Consume the project design system tokens for colors, typography, spacing. Ensure components render with the exact color values provided when rendering.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on Roam Resort Terms of Service page (static route).
2. User views the hero/header and reads the sections detailing rules and disclaimers.
3. User notes the “Last Updated” date and can click a contact link for legal inquiries.
4. If a user wants to know more about privacy rights, they click the Privacy & Data Rights link (in-sections or footer) to navigate to privacy tools or CMS-managed page.
5. The user experiences clean, distraction-free reading with a premium feel consistent with Roam Resort’s brand.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models:
- TermsSection
  - id: string
  - title: string
  - body: string
  - bullets?: string[]
  - disclaimer?: string
- TermsPageContent (optional CMS support)
  - locale: string
  - lastUpdated: string (ISO date)
  - sections: TermsSection[]
- (Optional) PrivacyRequest (future integration)
  - id: string
  - userId: string
  - type: 'export' | 'delete'
  - status: string
  - requestedAt: string
  - completedAt?: string

API Endpoints:
- Not required for rendering, but ready in codebase for future: 
  - GET /api/terms?locale=xx -> TermsPageContent
  - POST /api/privacy/requests -> create PrivacyRequest (future)
Security:
- Frontend-only read access for this page; no sensitive data exposed.
- If hosting CMS data, ensure proper token-based access or read-only public access for static content.

Validation:
- All incoming content must be validated for shape before rendering:
  - const sections = Array.isArray(data?.sections) ? data.sections : []
  - For each section, title and body must be strings; bullets, if present, must be an array of strings.

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project’s design system:
- Use the provided color palette, typography, spacing, and card styles.
- Maintain editorial look with large imagery (if used in hero or section visuals) and ample whitespace.
- Ensure consistent alignment: center hero CTAs, left-aligned detailed content.
- Cards, hover interactions, and micro-interactions should reflect premium, elegant aesthetics.

Visual Style

Color Palette:
- Primary: #23212A
- Secondary: #ECE1D4
- Accent: #A97C50
- Text: #F8F6F3 (headers) / #3A3732 (body)
- Details: Gradients with #B49587 to #23212A, #D1B7A1
- Use light beige over deep navy and bronze-gold CTAs as standard

Typography & Layout:
- Headlines: Playfair Display or similar serif
- Body/Text: Inter or Lato
- Hierarchy: Bold headlines, regular body
- Alignment: Hero CTAs centered, content left-aligned
- Spacing: 40–80px vertical spacing between sections; 24–32px internal padding
- Typography Treatments: Section labels uppercase, subtle emphasis

Key Design Elements

Card Design:
- Radius: 8–12px
- Borders: Light beige or translucent white
- Hover: Slight scale-up, bronze-gold accent
- Visual Hierarchy: Image at top (if used), bold title, details

Navigation:
- Top navbar, transparent over hero, solid on scroll
- Active states: bronze-gold underline
- Mobile: hamburger with slide-out

Data Visualization:
- Not required for this page; if charts are used elsewhere, follow palette and subtle styling guidelines

Interactive Elements:
- Buttons: Bronze-gold fill (#A97C50), white or navy text
- Secondary Buttons: Soft beige with bronze outline
- Forms: For future privacy tools; ensure accessible design if implemented

Design Philosophy
- Modern luxury editorial aesthetic
- Elegant, clear, high-touch experience
- Visual storytelling with editorial typography
- Serene, intuitive UX
- Reflect premium quality and bespoke service

Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety

CRITICAL: All generated code must guard against null/undefined values before array methods. Use:
- const items = data ?? []
- (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
- useState<Type[]>([]) for array state
- const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Optional chaining: obj?.property?.nested
- Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Terms page renders with semantic HTML, correct headings, and accessible navigation
- [ ] All arrays/maps are guarded using the runtime safety rules
- [ ] Last Updated date is displayed and localized
- [ ] Contact/Legal inquiries link is present and accessible
- [ ] Privacy Tools CTA is present in footer or section, routing correctly or prepared for future integration

UI/UX Guidelines Summary
- Align with Roam Resort’s luxury, editorial aesthetic
- Ensure readability, accessibility, and responsive behavior
